{"title_page": "Emilia Cundari", "text_new": "{{short description|Soprano opera singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Emilia Cundari\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Emilia_Cundari_died_2005.png\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = Portrait of Cundari dressed as Annina in La Traviata\n| caption          = Portrait of Cundari in 1958 as Annina in La Traviata taken by Louis Melancon \n| background       = solo_singer\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1930|09|07}}\n| birth_place      = Detroit, Michigan\n| origin           = \n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2005|01|06|1930|09|07}}\n| death_place      = Southfield, Michigan\n| genre            = [[Opera]]\n| occupation       = \n| instrument       = Soprano\n| years_active     = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label            =  \n}}\n\n'''Emilia Cundari''' (September 7, 1930-January 6, 2005) was a [[soprano]] [[opera|opera singer]] who was born in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]] and raised in [[Windsor, Ontario]]. She performed with the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in New York City and [[La Scala]] in Milan, Italy prior to retiring from performing to raise a family.\n\n==Early life and education==\nCundari was born in 1930 in Detroit, Michigan to Frank and Ambrosina Cundari.<ref name=\"Hill\">{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Sharon |title=Keeping the memory of Windsor\u2019s opera diva Emilia Cundari alive |url=https://windsorstar.com/news/local-news/keeping-the-memory-of-windsors-opera-diva-emilia-cundari-alive |accessdate=19 January 2019 |work=Windsor Star |date=7 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Her father co-owned and operated Mario's Restaurant in Windsor, Ontario where she attended Dougall Avenue School in addition to taking classes at the Ursuline School of Music.<ref name=\"Hill\" />  She later attended St. Mary's Academy where here vocal talent was apparent to teachers early on.<ref name=\"Mosaic\">{{cite web |last1=Gervais |first1=Marty |title=Emilia Cundari - Windsor's Operatic Star |url=http://www.windsor-communities.com/italian-music-cundari.php |website=Windsor Mosaic |accessdate=19 January 2019 |date=2005}}</ref> The school, operated by the [[Sisters of the Holy Names of Jesus and Mary]], began offering music training in 1864.<ref name=\"Hall&Wults\">{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Frederick A. |last2=Wults |first2=Philip M. |title=Music in Windsor |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/windsor-ont-emc |website=www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> Cundari went on to continue her studies at [[Marygrove College]] in Detroit, graduating with a bachelor of music.<ref name=\"WPLBio\">{{cite web |title=Emilia Cundari |url=http://www.windsorpubliclibrary.com/?page_id=61564 |website=Windsor Public Library |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> In hIn her early 20s, she was awarded a $2,000 Grinnell music scholarship, which allowed to travel to New York City where she continued her studies with conductor [[Max Rudolf (conductor)|Max Rudolf]] and the [[New York City Opera]].<ref name=\"WPLBio\" /><ref name=\"Mosaic\" /><ref name=\"Hill\" />\n\n==Career==\n\nCundari made her debut with the New York City Opera in 1953, performing as the Dew Fairy in ''[[Hansel and Gretel (opera)|Hansel and Gretel]]''. Two years later she was signed as a soprano with the [[Metropolitan Opera]], along with Madelaine Chambers.<ref name=\"NYTMetSigns\">{{cite news |title='Met' Signs 2 American Sopranos |work=New York Times |date=November 2, 1955 |page=41}}</ref>\nHer first performance as Barbarina in ''[[The Marriage of Figaro]]'' on March 1, 1956.<ref name=\"NYTFigaro1956\">{{cite news |title='FIGARO' AT THE 'MET': Miss Cundari Sings Barbarina First Time With Company |work=New York Times |date=March 2, 1956 |page=17}}</ref> Cundari debuted in a lead role with the company on March 19, 1957 as Micaela in a production of ''[[Carmen]]''. A reviewer for the New York Times said the role was well suited to her soprano voice calling her performance \"highly promising.\"<ref name=\"NYTCarmen\">{{cite news |last1=B. |first1=J. |title='CARMEN' SUNG AT 'MET': Emilia Cundari Makes First Appearance as Micaela |work=New York Times |date=March 11, 1957 |page=21}}</ref> She continued on in the role during a company tour that included a run at Maple Leaf Gardens in Toronto, Ontario.<ref name=\"Thomson\">{{cite news |last1=Thomson |first1=Hugh |title=Windsor's Emilia Cundari Shines as Carmen's Rival |work=Toronto Daily Star |date=May 31, 1957 |page=31}}</ref> In 1958 her performance as Lauretta in [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s ''[[Gianni Schicchi]]'' with the Met was reviewed by the paper as delivering a \"graceful and pretty\" performance that was in need of \"a little more assurance\" despite garnering applause for the aria \"O mio babbino caro\".<ref>{{cite news |title=CUNDARI, FLAGELLO PERFORM AT 'MET' |work=New York Times |date=February 18, 1958 |page=24}}</ref> \n\nFollowing her work with the Met, Cundari moved to Italy where she performed with [[La Scala]] in [[Milan]] and toured throughout Europe.<ref name=\"WPLBio\" /> In addition to live performances, Cundari appeared on several recordings including Beethoven's [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 9]] and Mahler's [[Symphony No. 2 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 2]] under the direction of conductor and composer [[Bruno Walter]].<ref name=\"Mosaic\" />  \n\nWhile in Italy Cundari met opera singer [[Sergio Pezzetti]], whom she married in 1965. Following the birth of their son, Cundari returned to Windsor where she occasionally performed and taught music.<ref name=\"Hill\" /> Despite multiple requests to perform abroad, Cundari spent the remainder of her life outside of the spotlight.<ref name=\"Mosaic\" />\n\n==Death and legacy==\nCundari died January 6, 2005, at the age of 74, in [[Southfield, Michigan]].<ref name=\"WindsorObit\">{{cite web |title=Remembering the life of Emilia Pezzetti 2005 |url=http://windsorstar.remembering.ca/obituary/emilia-pezzetti-2005-1066487367 |website=windsorstar.remembering.ca |accessdate=19 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Although she achieved international recognition in the 1950s and 1960s, her musical career remained largely unrecognized until after her death. Since that time, an opera about the lives of Cundari and photographer [[Pat Sturn]] was produced by cellist [[Nadine Deleury]] in 2014.<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=T. |title=Nadine Deleury\u2019s tale of two women |url=https://windsorstar.com/entertainment/nadine-deleurys-tale-of-two-women |accessdate=19 January 2019 |work=Windsor Star |date=20 December 2014 |language=en}}</ref> Four years later, a crowd-funding campaign to add a memorial plaque to the Windsor mausoleum, where Cundari was laid to rest, was launched by soprano [[Tara Sievers-Hunt]].<ref name=\"Hill\" /> It resulted in the installation of a bronze plaque featuring roses and crosses at the site of her previously unmarked crypt at Heavenly Rest Cemetery.<ref name=\"HillNotForgotten\">{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Sharon |title=Not forgotten \u2014 \u2018Windsor\u2019s Soprano\u2019 remembered with bronze plaque |url=https://windsorstar.com/news/local-news/not-forgotten-windsors-soprano-remembered-with-bronze-plaque |accessdate=19 January 2019 |work=Windsor Star |date=1 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\n*''Beethoven's Symphonies No. 9'' (1958) {{oclc|3364797}}\n*''Mahler's Symphony No. 2 : in C minor (Resurrection)'' {{oclc|224088634}}\n*''Antonio Vivaldi, Nisi Dominus, Magnificat'' (1961) {{oclc|878391447}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cundari, Emilia}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:American operatic sopranos]]\n[[Category:Singers from Detroit]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Soprano opera singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Emilia Cundari\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Emilia_Cundari_died_2005.png\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = Portrait of Cundari dressed as Annina in La Traviata\n| caption          = Portrait of Cundari in 1958 as Annina in La Traviata taken by Louis Melancon \n| background       = solo_singer\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1930|09|07}}\n| birth_place      = Detroit, Michigan\n| origin           = \n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2005|01|06|1930|09|07}}\n| death_place      = Southfield, Michigan\n| genre            = [[Opera]]\n| occupation       = \n| instrument       = Soprano\n| years_active     = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label            =  \n}}\n\n'''Emilia Cundari''' (September 7, 1930-January 6, 2005) was a [[soprano]] [[opera|opera singer]] who was born in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]] and raised in [[Windsor, Ontario]]. She performed with the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in New York City and [[La Scala]] in Milan, Italy prior to retiring from performing to raise a family.\n\n==Early life and education==\nCundari was born in 1930 in Detroit, Michigan to Frank and Ambrosina Cundari.<ref name=\"Hill\">{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Sharon |title=Keeping the memory of Windsor\u2019s opera diva Emilia Cundari alive |url=https://windsorstar.com/news/local-news/keeping-the-memory-of-windsors-opera-diva-emilia-cundari-alive |accessdate=19 January 2019 |work=Windsor Star |date=7 April 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Her father co-owned and operated Mario's Restaurant in Windsor, Ontario where she attended Dougall Avenue School in addition to taking classes at the Ursuline School of Music.<ref name=\"Hill\" />  She later attended St. Mary's Academy where here vocal talent was apparent to teachers early on.<ref name=\"Mosaic\">{{cite web |last1=Gervais |first1=Marty |title=Emilia Cundari - Windsor's Operatic Star |url=http://www.windsor-communities.com/italian-music-cundari.php |website=Windsor Mosaic |accessdate=19 January 2019 |date=2005}}</ref> The school, operated by the [[Sisters of the Holy Names of Jesus and Mary]], began offering music training in 1864.<ref name=\"Hall&Wults\">{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Frederick A. |last2=Wults |first2=Philip M. |title=Music in Windsor |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/windsor-ont-emc |website=www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> Cundari went on to continue her studies at [[Marygrove College]] in Detroit, graduating with a bachelor of music.<ref name=\"WPLBio\">{{cite web |title=Emilia Cundari |url=http://www.windsorpubliclibrary.com/?page_id=61564 |website=Windsor Public Library |accessdate=19 January 2019}}</ref> In hIn her early 20s, she was awarded a $2,000 Grinnell music scholarship, which allowed to travel to New York City where she continued her studies with conductor [[Max Rudolf (conductor)|Max Rudolf]] and the [[New York City Opera]].<ref name=\"WPLBio\" /><ref name=\"Mosaic\" /><ref name=\"Hill\" />\n\n==Career==\n\nCundari made her debut with the New York City Opera in 1953, performing as the Dew Fairy in ''[[Hansel and Gretel (opera)|Hansel and Gretel]]''. Two years later she was signed as a soprano with the [[Metropolitan Opera]], along with Madelaine Chambers.<ref name=\"NYTMetSigns\">{{cite news |title='Met' Signs 2 American Sopranos |work=New York Times |date=November 2, 1955 |page=41}}</ref>\nHer first performance as Barbarina in ''[[The Marriage of Figaro]]'' on March 1, 1956.<ref name=\"NYTFigaro1956\">{{cite news |title='FIGARO' AT THE 'MET': Miss Cundari Sings Barbarina First Time With Company |work=New York Times |date=March 2, 1956 |page=17}}</ref> Cundari debuted in a lead role with the company on March 19, 1957 as Micaela in a production of ''[[Carmen]]''. A reviewer for the New York Times said the role was well suited to her soprano voice calling her performance \"highly promising.\"<ref name=\"NYTCarmen\">{{cite news |last1=B. |first1=J. |title='CARMEN' SUNG AT 'MET': Emilia Cundari Makes First Appearance as Micaela |work=New York Times |date=March 11, 1957 |page=21}}</ref> She continued on in the role during a company tour that included a run at Maple Leaf Gardens in Toronto, Ontario.<ref name=\"Thomson\">{{cite news |last1=Thomson |first1=Hugh |title=Winsor's Emilia Cundari Shines as Carmen's Rival |work=Toronto Daily Star |date=May 31, 1957 |page=31}}</ref> In 1958 her performance as Lauretta in [[Giacomo Puccini]]'s ''[[Gianni Schicchi]]'' with the Met was reviewed by the paper as delivering a \"graceful and pretty\" performance that was in need of \"a little more assurance\" despite garnering applause for the aria \"O mio babbino caro\".<ref>{{cite news |title=CUNDARI, FLAGELLO PERFORM AT 'MET' |work=New York Times |date=February 18, 1958 |page=24}}</ref> \n\nFollowing her work with the Met, Cundari moved to Italy where she performed with [[La Scala]] in [[Milan]] and toured throughout Europe.<ref name=\"WPLBio\" /> In addition to live performances, Cundari appeared on several recordings including Beethoven's [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 9]] and Mahler's [[Symphony No. 2 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 2]] under the direction of conductor and composer [[Bruno Walter]].<ref name=\"Mosaic\" />  \n\nWhile in Italy Cundari met opera singer [[Sergio Pezzetti]], whom she married in 1965. Following the birth of their son, Cundari returned to Windsor where she occasionally performed and taught music.<ref name=\"Hill\" /> Despite multiple requests to perform abroad, Cundari spent the remainder of her life outside of the spotlight.<ref name=\"Mosaic\" />\n\n==Death and legacy==\nCundari died January 6, 2005, at the age of 74, in [[Southfield, Michigan]].<ref name=\"WindsorObit\">{{cite web |title=Remembering the life of Emilia Pezzetti 2005 |url=http://windsorstar.remembering.ca/obituary/emilia-pezzetti-2005-1066487367 |website=windsorstar.remembering.ca |accessdate=19 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Although she achieved international recognition in the 1950s and 1960s, her musical career remained largely unrecognized until after her death. Since that time, an opera about the lives of Cundari and photographer [[Pat Sturn]] was produced by cellist [[Nadine Deleury]] in 2014.<ref name=\"Shaw\">{{cite news |last1=Shaw |first1=T. |title=Nadine Deleury\u2019s tale of two women |url=https://windsorstar.com/entertainment/nadine-deleurys-tale-of-two-women |accessdate=19 January 2019 |work=Windsor Star |date=20 December 2014 |language=en}}</ref> Four years later, a crowd-funding campaign to add a memorial plaque to the Windsor mausoleum, where Cundari was laid to rest, was launched by soprano [[Tara Sievers-Hunt]].<ref name=\"Hill\" /> It resulted in the installation of a bronze plaque featuring roses and crosses at the site of her previously unmarked crypt at Heavenly Rest Cemetery.<ref name=\"HillNotForgotten\">{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Sharon |title=Not forgotten \u2014 \u2018Windsor\u2019s Soprano\u2019 remembered with bronze plaque |url=https://windsorstar.com/news/local-news/not-forgotten-windsors-soprano-remembered-with-bronze-plaque |accessdate=19 January 2019 |work=Windsor Star |date=1 August 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\n*''Beethoven's Symphonies No. 9'' (1958) {{oclc|3364797}}\n*''Mahler's Symphony No. 2 : in C minor (Resurrection)'' {{oclc|224088634}}\n*''Antonio Vivaldi, Nisi Dominus, Magnificat'' (1961) {{oclc|878391447}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cundari, Emilia}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:American operatic sopranos]]\n[[Category:Singers from Detroit]]\n", "name_user": "Elwood", "